#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:3
msgid "Building Packages Using Recipe"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:5
msgid ""
"While you can build Python packages from source, we provide a `conda`-style "
"recipe system to build multiple packages at once."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:8
msgid ""
"Using a recipe is also required to include the package in the Pyodide "
"distribution. See {ref}`adding-packages-into-pyodide-distribution` for more "
"information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:11
msgid "Creating the `meta.yaml` file"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:13
msgid ""
"To build a Python package in tree, you need to create a `meta.yaml` file "
"that defines a recipe which includes build commands and patches (source code "
"edits), amongst other things."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:17
msgid ""
"If your package is on PyPI, the easiest place to start is with the `pyodide "
"skeleton pypi` command. Run"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:20
msgid "pyodide skeleton pypi <package-name>\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:24
msgid ""
"This will generate a `meta.yaml` file under `packages/<package-name>/` (see "
"{ref}`meta-yaml-spec`). The `pyodide` cli tool will populate the latest "
"version, the download link and the sha256 hash by querying PyPI."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:28
msgid ""
"It doesn't currently handle package dependencies, so you will need to "
"specify those yourself in the `requirements` section of the `meta.yaml` file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:31
msgid ""
"requirements:\n"
"  host:\n"
"    # Dependencies that are needed to build the package\n"
"    - numpy\n"
"  run:\n"
"    # Dependencies that are needed to run the package\n"
"    - numpy\n"
"    - scikit-learn\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:43
msgid ""
"To determine build and runtime dependencies, including for non Python "
"libraries, it is often useful to check if the package was already built on "
"[conda-forge](https://conda-forge.org/) look at the corresponding `meta."
"yaml` file. This can be done either by checking if the URL `https://github."
"com/conda-forge/<package-name>-feedstock/blob/master/recipe/meta.yaml` "
"exists, or by searching the [conda-forge GitHub org](https://github.com/"
"conda-forge/) for the package name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:51
msgid ""
"The Pyodide `meta.yaml` file format was inspired by the one in conda, "
"however it is not strictly compatible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:55
msgid "Building Recipes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:57
msgid ""
"Once the `meta.yaml` file is ready, build the package with the following "
"command and see if there are any errors."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:60
msgid "pyodide build-recipes <package-name> --install\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:64
msgid ""
"This command will build the package and all its dependencies. The `--"
"install` The `--install` flag will install the built package into the `/"
"dist` directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:67
msgid "Testing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:69
msgid ""
"If the build succeeds you can try to load the package in the Pyodide "
"environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:71
msgid ""
"Visit Build Pyodide or download the latest release from the GitHub "
"repository."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:72
msgid ""
"Copy everything built in the `/dist` directory to the downloaded Pyodide "
"directory. This should include the `pyodide-lock.json` file and the wheel "
"files that were built."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:75
msgid ""
"Serve the Pyodide directory with `python -m http.server --directory ./dist`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:76
msgid "Open `localhost:8000/console.html` and try to import the package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:77
msgid "You can test the package in the repl."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:79
msgid "Modifying Build Process"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:81
msgid ""
"If you need to modify the build process (e.g. to fix build issues) you can "
"do this by modifying the `meta.yaml` file. The `build` section of the `meta."
"yaml` is where you can run scripts, set environment variables, and add extra "
"compile and link flags."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:86
msgid ""
"build:\n"
"  # You can add any shell scripts you want to run before invoking the "
"build.\n"
"  # For instance, setting environment variables or downloading files, or "
"modifying the source can be done here.\n"
"  script: |\n"
"    wget https://example.com/file.tar.gz\n"
"    export MY_ENV_VARIABLE=FOO\n"
"  # You can pass extra compile and link flags to the compiler by adding them "
"here.\n"
"  cflags: |\n"
"    -O3\n"
"  cxxflags: |\n"
"    -O3\n"
"  ldflags: |\n"
"    -lm\n"
"  # This is the command that is passed to the build backend. For example, if "
"you\n"
"  # need to pass extra flags to setuptools, you can pass them here.\n"
"  backend-flags: |\n"
"    setup-args=-Dallow-noblas=true\n"
"  # post is a script that is run after the build. This is useful for\n"
"  # post-processing the wheel file.\n"
"  post: |\n"
"    rm unnecessary-file-in-the-wheel.txt\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:110
msgid "Patching the package source"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:112
msgid ""
"If the package has a bug that needs to be fixed, you can apply `.patch` "
"files to the package source. This is commonly done when the package requires "
"special handling for Emscripten or Pyodide environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:116
msgid ""
"Place the patch files in the `patches` directory of the package, and specify "
"them in the `source.patches` section of the `meta.yaml` file. The patches "
"will be applied in the order they are listed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:120
msgid ""
"source:\n"
"  patches:\n"
"    - patches/0001-Add-Wno-return-type-flag.patch\n"
"    - patches/0002-Align-xerbla_array-signature-with-scipy-expectation."
"patch\n"
"    - patches/0003-Skip-linktest.patch\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:130
msgid "Generating patches"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:132
msgid ""
"If the package has a git repository, the easiest way to make a patch is "
"usually:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:134
msgid ""
"Clone the git repository of the package. You might want to use the options "
"`git clone --depth 1 --branch <version>`. Find the appropriate tag given the "
"version of the package you are trying to modify."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:137
msgid ""
"Make a new branch with `git checkout -b pyodide-version` (e.g., "
"`pyodide-1.21.4`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:139
msgid ""
"Make whatever changes you want. Commit them. Please split your changes up "
"into focused commits. Write detailed commit messages! People will read them "
"in the future, particularly when migrating patches or trying to decide if "
"they are no longer needed. The first line of each commit message will also "
"be used in the patch file name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:144
msgid ""
"Use `git format-patch <version> -o packages/<package-name>/patches/` to "
"generate a patch file for your changes and store it directly into the "
"patches folder."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:148
msgid "Upstream your patches!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:150
msgid ""
"Please create PRs or issues to discuss with the package maintainers to try "
"to find ways to include your patches into the package. Many package "
"maintainers are very receptive to including Pyodide-related patches and they "
"reduce future maintenance work for us."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:155
msgid "Upgrading a package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:157
msgid "To upgrade a package's version to the latest one available on PyPI, do"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:159
msgid "pyodide skeleton pypi <package-name> --update\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:163
msgid ""
"Because this does not handle package dependencies, you have to manually "
"check whether the `requirements` section of the `meta.yaml` file needs to be "
"updated for updated dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:167
msgid ""
"Upgrading a package's version may lead to new build issues that need to be "
"resolved (see above) and any patches need to be checked and potentially "
"migrated (see below)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:170
msgid "Migrating Patches"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:172
msgid ""
"When you want to upgrade the version of a package, you will need to migrate "
"the patches. To do this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:175
msgid ""
"Clone the git repository of the package. You might want to use the options "
"`git clone --depth 1 --branch <version-tag>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:177
msgid ""
"Make a new branch with `git checkout -b pyodide-old-version` (e.g., "
"`pyodide-1.21.4`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:179
msgid ""
"Apply the current patches with `git am packages/<package-name>/patches/*`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:180
msgid ""
"Make a new branch `git checkout -b pyodide-new-version` (e.g., "
"`pyodide-1.22.0`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:182
msgid ""
"Rebase the patches with `git rebase old-version --onto new-version` (e.g., "
"`git rebase pyodide-1.21.4 --onto pyodide-1.22.0`). Resolve any rebase "
"conflicts. If a patch has been upstreamed, you can drop it with `git rebase "
"--skip`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:185
msgid "Remove old patches with `rm packages/<package-name>/patches/*`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:186
msgid ""
"Use `git format-patch <version-tag> -o packages/<package-name>/patches/` to "
"generate new patch files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:189
msgid "Appendix"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:191
msgid "C library dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:193
msgid ""
"Some Python packages depend on certain C libraries, e.g. `lxml` depends on "
"`libxml`. Pyodide recipes can also be used to build C libraries."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:196
msgid ""
"To package a C library, create a directory for it and add `meta.yaml` file "
"similar to the one for Python packages. However, unlike the Python package, "
"you need to specify a build script that builds the C library. See {ref}`meta-"
"yaml-spec` for more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:201
msgid ""
"The minimal example of `meta.yaml` for a C library that uses `configure` and "
"`make` is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:204
msgid ""
"package:\n"
"  name: <name>\n"
"  version: <version>\n"
"\n"
"source:\n"
"  url: <url>\n"
"  sha256: <sha256>\n"
"\n"
"requirements:\n"
"  run:\n"
"    - <requirement>\n"
"\n"
"build:\n"
"  type: static_library\n"
"  script: |\n"
"    emconfigure ./configure\n"
"    emmake make\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:224
msgid ""
"You can use the `meta.yaml` of other C libraries such as [libxml](https://"
"github.com/pyodide/pyodide-recipes/blob/main/packages/libxml/meta.yaml) as a "
"starting point."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:228
msgid ""
"After packaging a C library, it can be added as a dependency of a Python "
"package like a normal dependency. See `lxml` and `libxml` for an example "
"(and also `scipy` and `OpenBLAS`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:232
msgid ""
"_Remark:_ Certain C libraries come as emscripten ports, and do not have to "
"be built manually. They can be used by adding e.g. `-s USE_ZLIB` in the "
"`cflags` of the Python package. See e.g. `matplotlib` for an example. [The "
"full list of libraries with Emscripten ports is here.](https://github.com/"
"orgs/emscripten-ports/repositories?type=all)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:238
msgid "Rust/PyO3 Packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:240
msgid ""
"We currently build `cryptography` which is a Rust extension built with PyO3 "
"and `setuptools-rust`. It should be reasonably easy to build other Rust "
"extensions. If you want to build a package with Rust extension, you will "
"need Rust >= 1.41, and you need to set the rustup toolchain to `nightly`, "
"and the target to `wasm32-unknown-emscripten` in the build script [as shown "
"here](https://github.com/pyodide/pyodide-recipes/blob/main/packages/"
"cryptography/meta.yaml), but other than that there may be no other issues if "
"you are lucky."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:248
msgid ""
"As mentioned [here](https://github.com/pyodide/pyodide/"
"issues/2706#issuecomment-1154655224), by default certain wasm-related "
"`RUSTFLAGS` are set during `build.script` and can be removed with `export "
"RUSTFLAGS=\"\"`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:252
msgid ""
"If your project builds using maturin, you need to use maturin 0.14.14 or "
"later. It is pretty easy to patch an existing project (see `projects/"
"fastparquet/meta.yaml` for an example)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:255
msgid "Partial Rebuilds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:257
msgid ""
"By default, each time you run `pyodide build-recipes`, it will delete the "
"entire source directory and replace it with a fresh copy from the download "
"url. This is to ensure build repeatability. For debugging purposes, this is "
"likely to be undesirable. If you want to try out a modified source tree, you "
"can pass the flag `--continue` and `build-recipes` will try to build from "
"the existing source tree. This can cause various issues, but if it works it "
"is much more convenient."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/building-packages-using-recipe.md:264
msgid ""
"Using the `--continue` flag, you can modify the sources in tree to fix the "
"build, then when it works, copy the modified sources into your checked out "
"copy of the package source repository and use `git format-patch` to generate "
"the patch."
msgstr ""
